1 Postsecondary Education. The funding model shall include a public university
2 sector formula and a KCTCS sector formula, and shall not include any race-based
3 metrics or targets in the formulas.
4 (5) The funding formula for the public university sector shall:
5 (a) Recognize differences in missions and cost structures between research
6 universities and comprehensive universities to ensure that neither are
7 advantaged or disadvantaged during the first full year of implementation;
8 (b) Distribute one hundred percent (100%) of the university allocable resources
9 for all universities in the sector, based on rational criteria, including student
10 success, course completion, and operational support components, regardless
11 of whether state funding for postsecondary institution operations increases,
12 decreases, or remains stable;
13 (c) Include an adjustment to minimize impact on smaller campuses as determined
14 by the council; and
15 (d) Be constructed to achieve equilibrium, at which point the funding formula
16 rewards rates of improvement above the sector average rate.
17 (6) Funding for the public university sector shall be distributed as follows:
18 (a) Forty percent (40%) of total university allocable resources shall be distributed
19 based on each university's share of total student success outcomes produced,
20 including but not limited to:
21 1. Bachelor's degree production;
22 2. Numbers of students progressing beyond thirty (30), sixty (60), and
23 ninety (90) credit hour thresholds;
24 3. Science, technology, engineering, math, and health bachelor's degree
25 production; and
26 4. Bachelor's degrees earned by low-income students and underrepresented
27 students;
